<P ALIGN="CENTER"><FONT SIZE="-1" COLOR="GREEN"><I>Rig Veda</I>, tr. by Ralph T.H. Griffith, [1896], at sacred-texts.com</FONT></P><HR></p>  <h3 align="center" align="center">HYMN LXV Mitra-Varu&#7751;a.</h3>  
<p>1. FULL wise is he who hath discerned: let him speak to us of the Gods,&#151;<br> The man whose praise-songs Varu&#7751;a the beautiful, or Mitra, loves.<br> 2 For they are Kings of noblest might, of glorious fame most widely spread;<br> Lords of the brave, who strengthen Law, the Holy Ones with every race.<br> 3 Approaching you with prayer for aid, together I address you first<br> We who have good steeds call on you, Most Sage, to give us strength besides.<br> 4 E&#146;en out of misery Mitra gives a way to dwelling at our case,<br> For he who worships hath the grace of Mitra, fighter in the van. '<br> 5 In Mitra's shelter that extends to utmost distance may we dwell,<br> Unmenaced, guarded by the care, ever as sons of Varu&#7751;a.<br> 6 Ye, Mitra, urge this people on, and to one end direct their ways.<br> Neglect not ye the wealthy chiefs, neglect not us the &#7770;&#7779;is: be our guardians when ye quaff the milk.</p>  
